ociety of Anglo-Saxonists 2017 Publication Prize: Best Edition The late tenth-century Old English Metrical Calendar (traditionally known as Menologium) summarises, in the characteristicheroic diction and traditional metre of Old English poetry, the major course of the Anglo-Saxon liturgical year. It sets out, in a methodical structure based on the basic temporal framework of the solar/natural year, the locations of the major feasts widely observed in late Anglo-Saxon England. Such a work could have been a practical timepiece for reading the dates of the Anglo-Saxon Chronicle, for which it serves as a kind of prologue in the manuscript.The clearly domestic perspective of the poem, which fits in the manuscript context, is also noteworthy, while the poem also reveals various interesting characteristics in its grammar, vocabulary and prosody. This is the firstfull modern edition of the poem, and is accompanied by a facing translation. The introduction provides an extensive discussion of matter, content, style, and context, while the commentary offers further information. The volume also includes the texts and translations of a number of analogous works. Kazutomo Karasawa is Professor of English philology at Komazawa University, Tokyo.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian martyrsvEarly works to 1800. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Saxon Chronicle.  aAnglo-Saxon England.  aAnglo-Saxon liturgy.  aAnglo-Saxon poetry.  aChristian festivals.  aChristian worship.  aDomestic perspective.  aEnglish philology.  aGrammar.  aKazutomo Karasawa.  aLiturgical year.  aMenologium.  aOld English Metrical Calendar.  aProsody.  aSolar/natural year.  aVocabulary.  acultural history.  aliturgical practices.  aliturgical traditions.  aliturgical year.  a